# CS 461 Program 2 — Video Script
## Genetic Algorithm Scheduler | ~6 minutes

---

## Cat (~2 minutes) — Data Model & Fitness Functions

**[Show schedule.py, rooms.py, activities.py on screen]**

"I built the data model for the program. The core unit is the Gene class — each Gene represents one activity assignment and holds four things: an Activity object, a time slot, a Room object, and a facilitator name. A Schedule is just a list of Genes with a fitness score."

"The Activity class stores the course name, expected enrollment, and two lists — preferred and other facilitators. The Room class stores the building name, room number, and capacity. Having these as objects instead of raw strings lets us access things like room capacity and facilitator preferences directly in the fitness functions."

**[Show fitness_functions.py on screen]**

"The fitness function scores a schedule by checking four things independently for each activity."

"First, room overlap — if two activities share the same room and time slot, each gets -0.5. Second, room size fit — too small is -0.5, way too big is -0.4, somewhat too big is -0.2, and a good fit is +0.3. The order of those checks matters — we had a bug early on where the 3x check came after the 1.5x check, so the bigger penalty was never reachable."

"Third, facilitator preference — preferred is +0.5, other listed is +0.2, unlisted is -0.1. Fourth, facilitator load — we check for time conflicts, consecutive slots, and total activity count. Dr. Tyler is a special case because he's committee chair, so he's exempt from the underload penalty if he has fewer than 2 activities."

"All of these individual scores get summed together with Ayan's activity-specific adjustments to produce the total fitness for a schedule."

