## Derek (~2 minutes) — Schedule Generator & GA Engine

**[Show Schedule_Generator.py on screen]**

"I built the schedule generator and the genetic algorithm engine. The generator reads from our CSV database — activities, rooms, time slots, and facilitators — and creates random schedules. Each schedule has the same 11 activities in the same order, but with randomly assigned rooms, times, and facilitators. We start with a population of 1,000 random schedules."

**[Show mutation.py on screen]**

"The GA engine has four main components. First, selection — we sort all schedules by fitness and kill the bottom 50%. Second, crossover — we randomly pair up survivors and splice their genes at a random index to produce two children per pair. This preserves good gene combinations from the parents."

"Third, mutation — for each gene in each child, there's a small chance we randomly re-roll its time, room, or facilitator. We never change which activity is at a position — that stays fixed. The mutation rate starts at 1% and adapts based on fitness improvement."

**[Show terminal output with generation stats]**

"Fourth, the generational loop — we run at least 100 generations. After that, if the average fitness improvement drops below 1%, we halve the mutation rate and keep going. We keep halving until the rate gets too small, then we stop. This lets the algorithm fine-tune in the later stages."

"You can see in the output that fitness climbs quickly in the first 30 generations, then plateaus around 12.4. When the mutation rate jumps to 5% during plateau periods, the worst fitness drops but it helps explore new solutions."

