## Ayan (~2 minutes) — Activity-Specific Adjustments & Visualization

**[Show cs_activity_specific_adjustments.py on screen]**

"I built the activity-specific fitness adjustments. These are the cross-activity rules that compare SLA 101 and SLA 191 sections against each other — they can't be scored by looking at one activity alone."

"The function checks three things. First, it checks whether the two sections of SLA 101 are far enough apart — more than 4 hours earns a bonus, same time slot is a penalty. Same logic for SLA 191 sections."

"Second, it checks all four cross-pairs between 101 and 191 sections. If a 101 section and a 191 section are in consecutive time slots, that's a +0.5 bonus — but if one of them is in Roman or Beach and the other isn't, there's a -0.4 building separation penalty because students would have to cross campus between back-to-back classes. If they're 2 hours apart, small bonus. Same time slot, small penalty."

"I also wrote a sanity test that creates a specific schedule designed to trigger multiple rule branches at once, so we can verify the math by hand. The expected score is 0.7 and the function returns exactly that."

**[Show visualization.py output and the fitness plot]**

"For visualization, I built the output module that prints the fitness stats table with generation-over-generation improvement percentages, the schedule in four formats — ordered by time, by activity, grouped by building, and grouped by facilitator — and the fitness line chart showing best, average, and worst scores across all generations."

**[Show the fitness plot]**

"Looking at the schedule the program produced — fitness of 12.4 — it's reasonable but not perfect. For example, Banks is teaching three consecutive time slots across different buildings, which isn't ideal. If I were to improve the fitness function, I'd add stronger penalties for facilitator back-to-back loads and maybe weight room fit more heavily so we don't see small classes in large rooms."

"The mutation rate strategy worked well — you can see in the plot that when mutation spikes to 5% during plateaus, the worst fitness drops temporarily but it helps the average recover. The key was halving the rate after 100 generations to let the algorithm converge without overshooting."

